Loading data files I have removed christmas day from data. I have filled missing values of variable event_type_1, event_type_2, event_name_1 and event_name_2 with No Event string This is for sales per state per department.

Model consideration: 1. Arimax 2. Arima + Fourier 3. Arfima

path     <- 'exported_sales_data/WithoutChristmas/'
data     <- vroom(str_c(path,'sales_per_dept_per_state_with_price_events_noChristmas.csv'), delim = ",", col_types = cols()) #_noChristmas
dept.ids  <- unique(data$dept_id)
state.ids <- unique(data$state_id)
for (i in dept.ids){
  for (j in state.ids){
    print(i)
    print(j)
    df1         <- data.frame(data[data$dept_id == i,])
    df          <- df1[df1$state_id == j,]
    EventName1  <- model.matrix(~as.factor(df$event_name_1))[,-1]
    EventName2  <- model.matrix(~as.factor(df$event_name_2))[,-1]
    test_len    <- nrow(df) - 27
    train       <- df[1: test_len, ]
    test        <- df[test_len:nrow(df), ]
    snap_col    <- paste('snap',j, sep="_")
    train.ts    <- ts(train$sales, frequency = 7)
    test.ts     <- ts(test$sales, frequency = 7)
    
    xreg.train  <- cbind(
                  MedianPrice = train[,"sell_price_median"],
                  IsWeekday   = train[,"Is_weekday"],
                  snap        = train[,snap_col],
                  event.name1 = EventName1[1: test_len, ],
                  event.name2 = EventName2[1: test_len, ]
                   )
                 
    model.arima <- auto.arima(train.ts, seasonal=TRUE, xreg=xreg.train)
  checkresiduals(model.arima)
  
   xreg.test <- cbind(
                  MedianPrice = test[,"sell_price_median"],
                  IsWeekday   = test[,"Is_weekday"],
                  snap        = test[,snap_col],
                  event.name1 = EventName1[test_len:nrow(df), ],
                  event.name2 = EventName2[test_len:nrow(df), ]
                  )
  forecast.arima <- forecast(model.arima, xreg = xreg.test, h=28)
  print(accuracy(forecast.arima, test$sales))
  }
}

Here I am combining fourier terms with ARIMA errors per department per state

for (i in dept.ids){
  for (j in state.ids){
    print(i)
    print(j)
    df1         <- data.frame(data[data$dept_id == i,])
    df          <- df1[df1$state_id == j,]
    test_len    <- nrow(df) - 27
    train       <- df[1: test_len, ]
    test        <- df[test_len:nrow(df), ]
    train.ts    <- ts(train$sales, frequency = 7)
    test.ts     <- ts(test$sales, frequency = 7)
    
    xreg.train  <- fourier(train.ts, K=3)
                 
    model.arima <- auto.arima(train.ts, seasonal=FALSE, xreg=xreg.train)
    checkresiduals(model.arima)
  
    xreg.test      <- fourier(test.ts, K=3, h=28)
    forecast.arima <- forecast(model.arima, xreg = xreg.test, h=28)
    print(accuracy(forecast.arima, test$sales))
  }
}

require(arfima)

## Loading required package: ltsa

## 1.4-0: type arfimachanges() for a list, as well as some other notes.
## NOTE: some of these are quite important!
## 
## Attaching package: 'arfima'
## The following object is masked from 'package:forecast':
## 
##     arfima
## The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     BIC
for (i in dept.ids){
  for (j in state.ids){
    print(i)
    print(j)
    df1          <- data.frame(data[data$dept_id == i,])
    df           <- df1[df1$state_id == j,]
    arfima.model <- forecast::arfima(df$sales)
    arfima.res   <- residuals(arfima.model)
    plot(arfima.res, type = "l")
    acf(arfima.res)
  }
}
